# Japanese New Year
## Introduction
- One of Japan's most important holidays
- Celebrated from January 1st to 3rd
- Rich in traditions and customs
![bg right:40%](./assets/images/new_year_background.jpg)

---

# Shishimai (Lion Dance)
- Traditional New Year's performance
- Brings good luck and wards off evil spirits
- Performed at shrines and festivals
![bg right:40%](./assets/images/shishimai.png)

---

# Kadomatsu
- Traditional decoration placed at entrances
- Made of bamboo and pine
- Welcomes ancestral spirits and deities
![bg right:40%](./assets/images/kadomatsu.png)

---

# Kagami Mochi
- Traditional New Year's decoration
- Two round mochi with a mandarin orange
- Offering to the gods for good fortune
![bg right:40%](./assets/images/kagami_mochi.png)

---

# Otoshidama
- New Year's gift money for children
- Given in special decorated envelopes
- Important tradition for families
![bg right:40%](./assets/images/otoshidama.png)

---

# Conclusion
## Preserving Japanese Traditions
- Rich cultural heritage
- Important family connections
- Passing traditions to future generations
